8 An Act relating to crimes and punishments; amending
Section 2, Chapter 224, O.S.L. 2024 (21 O.S. Supp.
9 2024, Section 1795), which relates to unlawful
immigration; making certain acts unlawful; providing
10 penalties; providing for the posting of a cash bond;
remanding persons to the custody of the Department of
11 Corrections; directing the Department to notify
certain federal agency to arrange transportation; and
12 declaring an emergency.
13
14
15 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
16 SECTION 1. AMENDATORY Section 2, Chapter 224, O.S.L.
17 2024 (21 O.S. Supp. 2024, Section 1795), is amended to read as
18 follows:
19 Section 1795. A. As used in this section, the term "alien"
20 means any person not a citizen or national of the United States.
21 B. A person commits an impermissible occupation if the person
22 is an alien and willfully and without permission enters and remains
23 in the State of Oklahoma without having first obtained legal
24 authorization to enter the United States.
Req. No. 13036 Page 1

1 C. 1. Any person found to have committed an impermissible
2 occupation pursuant to the provisions of subsection B of this
3 section and who enters this state without having obtained the legal
4 authorization to enter the United States shall, upon conviction, be
5 guilty of a misdemeanor punishable by imprisonment in the county
6 jail for a term of not more than one (1) year, or by a fine of not
7 more than Five Hundred Dollars ($500.00), or by both such fine and
8 imprisonment. In addition, the person shall be required to leave
9 the state within seventy-two (72) hours following his or her
10 conviction or release from custody, whichever comes later.
11 2. Any second or subsequent offense for an impermissible
12 occupation pursuant to the provisions of subsection B of this
13 section, or any such offense committed during the commission of any
14 other crime shall, upon conviction, be guilty of a felony punishable
15 by imprisonment in the custody of the Department of Corrections for
16 a term of not more than two (2) years, or by a fine of not more than
17 One Thousand Dollars ($1,000.00), or by both such fine and
18 imprisonment. In addition, the person shall be required to leave
19 the state within seventy-two (72) hours following his or her
20 conviction or release from custody, whichever comes later Any person
21 who is apprehended and arrested for violating a criminal law of this
22 state, and after determining the citizenship status of the person is
23 found to be unlawfully present in the United States, shall be guilty
24 of a felony punishable by imprisonment in the custody of the
Req. No. 13036 Page 2

1 Depa rtment of Corrections for a term of not less than five (5)
2 years.
3 C. A person arrested for a violation of this section may be
4 allowed to post a cash bond in an amount of not less than Thirty-
5 five Thousand Dollars ($35,000.00).
6 D. In lieu of the sentence of imprisonment, the court shall
7 have the authority to dismiss the criminal prosecution and issue a
8 written order discharging the person and requiring said individual
9 to return to his or her country of origin if:
10 1. The person agrees to the written order;
11 2. The person has not previously been convicted of a violent
12 crime, as provided for in Section 571 of Title 57 of the Oklahoma
13 Statutes, in this state or another state; and
14 3. The person is not charged with another felony offense.
15 Upon issuance of the written order, the court shall direct the
16 law enforcement agency having custody of the person to remand the
17 person to the custody of the Department of Corrections with
18 instructions to return the person to his or her country of origin.
19 E. Once the Department of Corrections receives custody of the
20 person, the Department of Corrections shall notify the United States
21 Customs and Border Protection of the Department of Homeland Security
22 within seven (7) days to arrange transportation for the repatriation
23 of said person back to his or her country of origin.
24
